{
  "answer": "**The opening couplet (maṭlaʿ) of the ghazal titled \"Dil hi to hai na sang-o-khisht, dard se bhar na aaye kyun-\" (Diwan-E-Ghalib, chapter 33) directly makes this comparison.**[^1]\n\n**Transliteration:**  \nDil hi to hai na sang-o-khisht, dard se bhar na aaye kyun?  \nRoyenge hum hazaar baar, koi hamein sataaye kyun?[^2]\n\n**Translation:**  \nIt is a heart, not stone and brick, that fills with pain;  \nWe'll weep a thousand times—why should a soul be slain?[^3]\n\nThis sher contrasts the heart's sensitivity (capable of holding pain, unlike inert stone and brick) with the expectation that it endure torment without overflowing into tears.\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [chapter](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/33-dil-hi-to-hai-na-sang-o-khisht-dard-se-bhar-na-aay/translation/).\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/33-dil-hi-to-hai-na-sang-o-khisht-dard-se-bhar-na-aay/transliteration/#p-4585fc).\n[^3]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/33-dil-hi-to-hai-na-sang-o-khisht-dard-se-bhar-na-aay/translation/#p-d9d50d).",
